lessons.theory:
## Heap Memory
Use `malloc` from `<stdlib.h>` to allocate memory dynamically. You must `free` it to prevent leaks.
```c
int *arr = (int*)malloc(5 * sizeof(int));
free(arr);
```

lessons.starterCode:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    int *arr = (int*)___(3 * sizeof(___));
    arr[0] = 100;
    ___(arr);
    return 0;
}

lessons.solution:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
int main() {
    int *arr = (int*)malloc(3 * sizeof(int));
    arr[0] = 100;
    free(arr);
    return 0;
}

lessons.theory:
## Structs
Group different variables under one name. `typedef` creates an alias for the struct type.
```c
typedef struct { int x; int y; } Point;
Point p = {10, 20};
```

lessons.starterCode:
#include <stdio.h>

typedef ___ {
    int id;
    int age;
} User;

int main() {
    User u = {1, 25};
    printf("ID: %d\n", u.___);
    return 0;
}

lessons.solution:
#include <stdio.h>
typedef struct {
    int id;
    int age;
} User;
int main() {
    User u = {1, 25};
    printf("ID: %d\n", u.id);
    return 0;
}

lessons.theory:
## File Operations
Use `fopen` to open a file. Mode `"r"` is read, `"w"` is write.
```c
FILE *fp = fopen("data.txt", "w");
fprintf(fp, "Hello");
fclose(fp);
```

lessons.starterCode:
